It is not to be confused with the [[Kumano Shrine|Kumano Sanzan]] shrine complex in [[Wakayama Prefecture]]. Its deity, known under the name 'Izanagi-no-Himanago Kaburogi Kumano-no-Ōkami Kushimikenu-no-Mikoto' (伊邪那伎日真名子加夫呂伎熊野大神櫛御気野命, "Beloved Child of Izanagi, Divine Ancestor [and] Great Deity of Kumano, Kushimikenu-no-Mikoto'), is identified with Susanoo.<ref>{{cite web |title=大神様のお話 |url=http://www.kumanotaisha.or.jp/ohanashi.gif |access-date=2020-03-30 |website=出雲國一之宮 熊野大社 (Kumano Taisha Official Website)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Kumano Taisha Shrine |url=http://www.kumanotaisha.or.jp/susanoo-e.htm |access-date=2020-03-30 |website=出雲國一之宮 熊野大社 (Kumano Taisha Official Website)}}</ref> The shrine is also considered in myth to be where [[Control of fire by early humans|the use of fire]] originated; two ancient [[Fire making|fire-making tools]], a [[Bow drill|hand drill]] (燧杵 ''hikiri-kine'') and a hearthboard (燧臼 ''hikiri-usu'') are kept in the shrine and used in the shrine's Fire Lighting Ceremony (鑚火祭 ''Kiribi-matsuri'' or ''Sanka-sai'') held every October.<ref>{{cite web |title=熊野大社 (Kumano Taisha) |url=http://furusato.sanin.jp/p/area/matsue/34/ |access-date=2020-03-30 |website=山陰観光【神々のふるさと山陰】}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=燧臼・燧杵―ひきりうす・ひきりぎね― |url=http://www.kumanotaisha.or.jp/saiten/sanka/hikiri.htm |access-date=2020-03-30 |website=出雲國一之宮 熊野大社 (Kumano Taisha Official Website)}}</ref>

